definition.value: A monocarboxylic acid amide that is lactic acid in which the carboxylic acid group has been converted to the corresponding carboxamide.
A dicarboxylic acid monoester that is succinic acid in which one of the carboxy groups has been converted to its methyl ester.
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 2-acyl substituent is specified as oleoyl.
An organic chloride salt having tetrazolium violet(1+) as the counterion.
An organic chloride salt having tetrazolium blue(1+) as the counterion.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of sodium molybdate.
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 2-acyl substituent is specified as acetyl.
An inorganic sodium salt having molybdate as the counterion.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as octadecyl
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as palmitoyl and acetyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and acetyl respectively.
An inorganic sodium salt having metavanadate as the counterion.
An inorganic sodium salt having periodate as the counterion.
An inorganic sodium salt having metaborate as the counterion.
An organic sodium salt having lactate as the counterion.
An inorganic sodium salt having bromate as the counterion.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while the acyl group at position 2 is palmitoleoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine O-38:4 in which the alkyl and acyl groups specified at positions 1 and 2 are octadecyl and (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-eicosatetraenoyl respectively.

A semisynthetic member of the class of rifamycins and non-systemic gastrointestinal site-specific broad spectrum antibiotic. Used in the treatment of traveller's diarrhoea, hepatic encephalopathy and irritable bowel syndrome.
A potassium salt consisting of potassium and tellurite ions in a 2:1 ratio.
A potassium salt consisting of potassium and chromate ions in a 2:1 ratio.

A pyridopyrimidine that is 5-oxo-5,8-dihydropyrido[2,3-d]pyrimidine-6-carboxylic acid substituted at position 2 by a piperazin-1-yl group and at position 8 by an ethyl group. A synthetic broad-spectrum antibacterial, it is used for treatment of gastrointestinal, biliary, and urinary infections.
Tetracycline in which a hydrogen attached to the amide nitrogen is substituted by a 4-[(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl]methyl group.
A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine betaine in which the alkyl and the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are hexadecyl and oleoyl respectively.

An organic sodium salt having tetradecyl sulfate as the counterion. Used in the treatment of small uncomplicated varicose veins of the lower extremities that show simple dilation with competent valves.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while the acyl group at position 2 is palmitoyl.
A phospholipid that is the hexadecyl monoester of phosphocholine.
A 1-O-(alk-1-enyl)-2-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine having palmitoyl as the 2-acyl group.
A  2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine betaine where the alkyl and the acyl groups at position 1 and 2 are octadecyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:0 where the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are icosanoyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 26:0 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are palmitoyl and decanoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are palmitoyl and hexanoyl respectively.
A  phosphatidylcholine 24:0 where the acyl groups at position 1 and 2 are palmitoyl and capryloyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 30:0 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) and myristoyl (tetradecanoyl) respectively.
An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid with a nitro substituent at position 4.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and (11Z)-octadecenoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and (6Z)-octadecenoyl respectively.

An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-glucoside of 3-hydroxy-1H-indole in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively. It is used to test for the presence of an enzyme, beta-glucosidase, which cleaves the glycosidic bond to give 5-bromo-4-chloro-3-hydroxy-1H-indole, which immediately dimerises to give an intensely blue product.
Any  fatty acid in which at least one of the aliphatic hydrogens is replaced by deuterium.
The meso diastereoisomer of butane-2,3-diol.
A phosphocholine that is the mono-1-elaidyl ester of phosphocholine
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of octanoic (caprylic) acid with the hydroxy group of 5-bromo-4-chloroindoxyl.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the alpha-D-mannoside of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the alpha-D-galactoside of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-glucuronide of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-glucosaminide of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
A glycol that is hexadecane which is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 2.
A 4-amino-1,2-oxazolidin-3-one that has S configuration. An antibiotic isolated from Erwinia uredovora.
A carboxamide that is a hydroxamic acid in which the hydrogen of the hydroxy group is replaced by an organyl group.
